<DOC><DOCNO> AP880913-0272 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 2017EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-American-Bass     09-13 0269</FIRST><SECOND>AM-American-Bass,0279</SECOND><HEAD>Bass Group Seeking Partner in Savings andamp; Loan Bailout</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bass investment group is seeking a partnerto finance part of its planned acquisition of American Savings andamp;Loan Association, according to the federal official overseeing a $2billion government bailout of the thrift.   The Robert M. Bass Group of Fort Worth, Texas, is negotiatingwith at least three companies as it seeks a partner, said M. DannyWall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.   Wall, whose comments outside a savings and loan group's meetinghere were reported Tuesday in the Wall Street Journal, did notrespond to a telephone request for comment.   Wall did not reveal the identities of the potential partnersexcept to say they were financial services companies. They were notfederally insured banks or savings and loan institutions, he said.   The Bass Group, which will gain control of American in exchangefor an injection of $550 million, can sell as much as 49 percent ofthe recapitalized American to a partner approved by the bank board,Wall said.   The bank board, which will own 30 percent of American, haspledged an estimated $2 billion in cash and promissory notes overthe next 10 years to rescue the insolvent institution.   The bank board seized Stockton-based American last week as aprelude to turning it over the Bass. American's 186 Californiabranches remain open, and federal insurance remains in force forall deposits.   Financial Corp. of America, the holding company for American,filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of thefederal bankruptcy code last week.</TEXT></DOC>